hands_on_practices.solution:
We use that an infinitesimal canonical transformation with generator $G(x,y,p_x,p_y)$ acts via
$$\delta f \;=\;\epsilon\{f,G\},\qquad 
\{f,G\}=\sum_{i=x,y}\Bigl(\frac{\partial f}{\partial q_i}\frac{\partial G}{\partial p_i}-\frac{\partial f}{\partial p_i}\frac{\partial G}{\partial q_i}\Bigr)\,. $$

1. From $\delta x=\epsilon\,\frac{p_y}{m\omega}=\epsilon\{x,G\}=\epsilon\,\frac{\partial G}{\partial p_x}$ we get
$$\frac{\partial G}{\partial p_x}=\frac{p_y}{m\omega}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
G=\frac{p_xp_y}{m\omega}+h(x,y)\,. $$

2. From $\delta y=\epsilon\,\frac{p_x}{m\omega}=\epsilon\,\{y,G\}=\epsilon\,\frac{\partial G}{\partial p_y}$ we find
$$\frac{\partial G}{\partial p_y}=\frac{p_x}{m\omega}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{\partial h}{\partial p_y}=0\;\Rightarrow\;h=h(x,y)\,. $$

3. From $\delta p_x=-\epsilon\,m\omega y=\epsilon\,\{p_x,G\}=-\epsilon\,\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}$ we get
$$\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}=m\omega y
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}=m\omega y
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
h(x,y)=m\omega\,x y+k(y)\,. $$

4. From $\delta p_y=-\epsilon\,m\omega x=\epsilon\,\{p_y,G\}=-\epsilon\,\frac{\partial G}{\partial y}$ we obtain
$$\frac{\partial G}{\partial y}=m\omega x
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
m\omega x+\frac{dk}{dy}=m\omega x
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
k' (y)=0\,. $$

Hence up to an irrelevant constant
$$G=\frac{p_xp_y}{m\omega}+m\omega\,x y\,, $$
which is conserved under the given symmetry.
